<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
     CHAPTER 9: STATISTICAL PHYSICS
═══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="sec-hdr" id="ch9">
  <div><div class="sec-num">Chapter 9</div><div class="sec-title" style="color:var(--s)">Statistical Physics</div></div>
  <span class="sec-tag st-s">§9.1 – 9.7</span>
</div>

<!-- S1: Maxwell Velocity Distribution -->
<div class="topic open" id="s1">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">9.2</span><div><div class="t-name">Maxwell Velocity & Speed Distribution</div><div class="t-sub">Classical distribution for ideal gas molecules</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-key">§9.2–9.4</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Maxwell velocity distribution</div>
      <div class="btext">In an ideal gas, each velocity component (vx, vy, vz) is independently distributed as a Gaussian. The 3D velocity distribution is:</div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Maxwell velocity distribution</div>
        f(v) = (m/2πkT)^(3/2) · exp(−mv²/2kT)
      </div>
      <div class="btext">This gives the probability per unit volume in velocity space of finding a molecule with velocity <strong>v</strong> = (vx, vy, vz).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Maxwell speed distribution F(v)</div>
      <div class="btext">To get a distribution in <em>speed</em> (scalar), integrate over all velocity directions — a shell of radius v in velocity space with area 4πv²:</div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Maxwell speed distribution</div>
        F(v) = 4π n (m/2πkT)^(3/2) · v² · exp(−mv²/2kT)
      </div>
      <div class="btext">The v² factor makes it zero at v=0, rises to a peak, then the exponential kills it at high v.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Three characteristic speeds</div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Most probable speed (peak of F(v) — set dF/dv = 0)</div>
        v_p = √(2kT/m)
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Average speed</div>
        ⟨v⟩ = √(8kT/πm)
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">RMS speed (from ½m⟨v²⟩ = 3/2 kT)</div>
        v_rms = √(3kT/m)
      </div>
      <div class="box box-s">Ordering: v_p &lt; ⟨v⟩ &lt; v_rms. The ratio is √2 : √(8/π) : √3 ≈ 1 : 1.13 : 1.22. Exam often asks you to identify which is which from a graph — v_p is the peak, v_rms is furthest right.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- S2: Equipartition -->
<div class="topic" id="s2">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">9.3</span><div><div class="t-name">Equipartition Theorem</div><div class="t-sub">Classical energy per degree of freedom</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-std">§9.3</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">The theorem</div>
      <div class="btext">In thermal equilibrium, each <strong>quadratic</strong> degree of freedom in the Hamiltonian carries an average energy of kT/2.</div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Energy per degree of freedom (classical)</div>
        ⟨E⟩ per DOF = ½kT
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Counting degrees of freedom</div>
      <div class="btext">Monatomic gas: 3 translational → U = 3/2 kT per molecule → C_v = 3/2 R per mole.<br><br>
      Diatomic gas (rigid): 3 translational + 2 rotational = 5 DOF → U = 5/2 kT → C_v = 5/2 R.<br><br>
      Diatomic (with vibration): add 2 more (KE + PE of vibration) = 7 DOF → C_v = 7/2 R.<br><br>
      Monatomic solid: 3 KE + 3 PE = 6 DOF → U = 3kT per atom → C_v = 3R = Dulong-Petit law.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Why it fails at low temperature</div>
      <div class="btext">Equipartition is classical — it assumes all modes are always excited. Quantum mechanically, a mode is only excited if kT ≳ ℏω (its energy quantum). At low T, vibrational modes are "frozen out" (kT ≪ ℏω), so they contribute less than kT/2. This is why measured C_v of diatomic gases is ~5/2 R at room temp, not 7/2 R.</div>
      <div class="box box-s">This is the historical motivation for quantum statistics — classical equipartition predicts too much heat capacity for solids at low T, and divergent energy for blackbody radiation (the UV catastrophe).</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- S3: Classical vs Quantum Statistics -->
<div class="topic" id="s3">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">9.5</span><div><div class="t-name">Classical vs Quantum Statistics</div><div class="t-sub">When MB applies, and when you must use FD or BE</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-key">§9.5</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">The three distribution functions</div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Maxwell-Boltzmann — classical, distinguishable, no restriction on occupancy</div>
        f_MB(E) = A · e^(−E/kT)
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Fermi-Dirac — fermions (half-integer spin), Pauli exclusion enforced</div>
        f_FD(E) = 1 / [e^((E−E_f)/kT) + 1]
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Bose-Einstein — bosons (integer spin), no restriction on occupancy</div>
        f_BE(E) = 1 / [e^((E−μ)/kT) − 1]
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">When does MB apply?</div>
      <div class="btext">MB is valid when the average occupation of any quantum state is <strong>much less than 1</strong> — i.e. particles are spread over far more states than there are particles. This happens at high T, low density, or large mass. MB is NOT a restriction — it just happens that double-occupancy never occurs in practice.<br><br>Formally, when e^((E−μ)/kT) ≫ 1 for all E, both FD and BE reduce to MB. The ±1 becomes negligible.</div>
      <div class="box box-s">Memory: MB = unlimited seating, nobody doubles up by chance. FD = Pauli physically forbids sharing. BE = bosons prefer to pile in. All three agree when states are mostly empty.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Symmetry of wave functions</div>
      <div class="btext">The root reason for the split: fermion wavefunctions are <strong>antisymmetric</strong> under particle exchange (ψ changes sign) → automatically enforces Pauli exclusion. Boson wavefunctions are <strong>symmetric</strong> → no exclusion, bunching preferred.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- S4: Fermi-Dirac -->
<div class="topic" id="s4">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">9.6</span><div><div class="t-name">Fermi-Dirac Statistics</div><div class="t-sub">Electrons in metals — Fermi energy, conduction theory</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-hot">§9.6 · most tested</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">The Fermi energy E_f</div>
      <div class="btext">At T = 0, f_FD is a perfect step function: all states below E_f are filled (f = 1), all above are empty (f = 0). The step drops sharply from 1 to 0 at <em>E = E_f</em>. As T increases, the step blurs symmetrically around E_f — states within ~kT of E_f smear.</div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Key identity — true at ALL temperatures</div>
        f_FD(E_f) = 1 / [e^0 + 1] = 1/2
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Fermi energy for a 3D free electron gas</div>
        E_f = (ℏ²/2m)(3π²n)^(2/3),   n = electron number density
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Fermi temperature T_f</div>
      <div class="btext">Defined as T_f = E_f / k. For copper, E_f ≈ 7 eV → T_f ≈ 81,000 K. Room temperature is 300 K ≪ T_f, so metals are always in the <strong>degenerate</strong> regime — quantum effects completely dominate. At T ≫ T_f, the step would wash out and electrons would follow MB.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Density of states g(E)</div>
      <div class="btext">f(E) gives probability of occupancy. g(E) gives how many states exist per unit energy. Both are needed:</div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">3D free electron density of states</div>
        g(E) ∝ E^(1/2)   (specifically: g(E) = (4π/h³)(2m)^(3/2) · E^(1/2))
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Number of electrons per unit volume per unit energy</div>
        n(E) = g(E) · f(E)
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Classical theory of electrical conduction (Drude model)</div>
      <div class="btext">Treat conduction electrons as a classical gas. Electrons accelerate under E field, scatter off ions with mean free time τ:</div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Drude conductivity</div>
        σ = ne²τ/m,   ρ = 1/σ = m/ne²τ
      </div>
      <div class="btext">Problem: Drude predicts electronic heat capacity = 3/2 Nk — far too large. Measured value is ~100× smaller.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Quantum theory of electrical conduction</div>
      <div class="btext">Only electrons within ~kT of E_f can be scattered or thermally excited — a tiny fraction kT/E_f of all electrons. This explains why electronic heat capacity is so small: <em>C_v ∝ T</em> (linear, not constant). Quantum model also gives the mean free path via the Fermi velocity v_f = √(2E_f/m), which is much faster than the classical thermal speed.</div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Fermi velocity</div>
        v_f = √(2E_f/m)
      </div>
      <div class="box box-s">Exam trap: "why is measured C_v for metals much less than classical prediction?" Answer: only electrons near E_f participate thermally. Classical Drude model assumes all electrons contribute equally — wrong.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- S5: Bose-Einstein -->
<div class="topic" id="s5">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">9.7</span><div><div class="t-name">Bose-Einstein Statistics</div><div class="t-sub">Blackbody radiation, liquid helium, BEC</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-key">§9.7</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Photons: blackbody radiation</div>
      <div class="btext">Photons are spin-1 bosons with μ = 0 (photon number not conserved — freely created/absorbed). Average number of photons per mode:</div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Planck distribution</div>
        ⟨n⟩ = 1 / [e^(hf/kT) − 1]
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Planck spectral energy density</div>
        u(f,T) = (8πhf³/c³) / [e^(hf/kT) − 1]
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Wien's displacement law</div>
        λ_max · T = 2.898 × 10⁻³ m·K
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-s">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Stefan-Boltzmann law (total power per unit area)</div>
        P/A = σT⁴,   σ = 5.67 × 10⁻⁸ W/m²K⁴
      </div>
      <div class="box box-s">UV catastrophe: classical Rayleigh-Jeans gives u ∝ f² → infinite total energy. Planck's quantization adds the e^(hf/kT) denominator, which crushes the distribution at high f.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Liquid helium & superfluidity</div>
      <div class="btext">⁴He atoms are bosons (even number of fermions → integer total spin). Below T_λ = 2.17 K, ⁴He becomes a <strong>superfluid</strong> — zero viscosity, flows without friction. This is a macroscopic quantum phenomenon: a macroscopic fraction of atoms condense into the single lowest energy state (Bose-Einstein condensation).<br><br>
      ³He atoms are fermions (odd total spin). They become superfluid only below ~2.6 mK through a Cooper-pair-like mechanism — pairs of ³He atoms form composite bosons.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Bose-Einstein condensation (BEC)</div>
      <div class="btext">Below a critical temperature T_c, a macroscopic fraction of bosons pile into the ground state — they all share the same quantum state. This is the BE analogue of the FD Fermi sea. First demonstrated in 1995 in dilute atomic gases (Rb, Na) at ~100 nK. Nobel Prize 2001.</div>
      <div class="box box-s">Symmetry of boson wavefunctions: if you exchange two identical bosons, ψ → +ψ (symmetric). This is what allows and even encourages multiple occupancy of the same state — unlike fermions where ψ → −ψ forces Pauli exclusion.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

