<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
     CHAPTER 10: MOLECULES & SOLIDS
═══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="sec-hdr" id="ch10">
  <div><div class="sec-num">Chapter 10</div><div class="sec-title" style="color:var(--m)">Molecules & Solids</div></div>
  <span class="sec-tag st-m">§10.1 – 10.6</span>
</div>

<!-- M1: Molecular Bonding & Spectra -->
<div class="topic open" id="m1">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">10.1</span><div><div class="t-name">Molecular Bonding & Spectra</div><div class="t-sub">Bond types, bonding/antibonding orbitals, rot & vib energy levels</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-hot">§10.1 · most tested</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Types of molecular bonds</div>
      <div class="box box-m">
        <strong>Ionic</strong>: electron transfer (Na⁺Cl⁻). Electrostatic attraction. ~1–4 eV binding.<br>
        <strong>Covalent</strong>: shared electrons (H₂, C-C). Quantum origin — see below. Strongest bonds.<br>
        <strong>van der Waals</strong>: induced dipole-dipole (noble gases, DNA bases). Very weak, ~meV.<br>
        <strong>Hydrogen bond</strong>: partially shared H between electronegative atoms (water, DNA). ~0.1–0.5 eV.<br>
        <strong>Metallic</strong>: electrons delocalized across lattice (Na, Cu). Free electron sea.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Bonding & antibonding orbitals (covalent bond origin)</div>
      <div class="btext">Take two hydrogen atoms. Each has a 1s wavefunction ψ_A and ψ_B. When atoms approach, form two superpositions:</div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Symmetric (even) superposition → bonding orbital</div>
        ψ₊ = ψ_A + ψ_B
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Antisymmetric (odd) superposition → antibonding orbital</div>
        ψ₋ = ψ_A − ψ_B
      </div>
      <div class="btext"><strong>Bonding (ψ₊)</strong>: constructive interference → electron density builds up <em>between</em> nuclei → screens nuclear repulsion → lowers energy → stable bond. Equilibrium bond length ~1.1 Å for H₂⁺.<br><br>
      <strong>Antibonding (ψ₋)</strong>: destructive interference → node between nuclei → electron density pushed <em>away</em> → nuclei repel → energy increases with decreasing r → no stable bond.</div>
      <div class="box box-m">This is the microscopic origin of bands in solids. Scale to N atoms: each bonding/antibonding pair splits into N levels → the levels are so closely spaced they form a continuous <strong>band</strong>. Bonding states = bottom of band, antibonding = top.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Rotational energy levels</div>
      <div class="btext">Diatomic molecule rotating about center of mass. Quantum number ℓ = 0, 1, 2, …</div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Rotational energy</div>
        E_rot = ℓ(ℓ+1) ℏ²/2I,   I = μr²,   μ = m₁m₂/(m₁+m₂)
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Selection rule for electric dipole rotational transitions</div>
        Δℓ = ±1 (molecule must have permanent dipole moment)
      </div>
      <div class="btext">Transition ℓ → ℓ−1 emits photon of energy ΔE = ℏ²ℓ/I. Energy spacings ~meV → <strong>microwave spectroscopy</strong>. Lines are equally spaced in frequency.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Vibrational energy levels</div>
      <div class="btext">Near equilibrium the potential is parabolic → quantum harmonic oscillator, n = 0, 1, 2, …</div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Vibrational energy</div>
        E_vib = (n + ½)hf₀,   f₀ = (1/2π)√(κ/μ)
      </div>
      <div class="btext">κ = bond spring constant. Zero-point energy = hf₀/2 even at n = 0. Spacings ~0.1 eV → <strong>infrared spectroscopy</strong>. Selection rule: Δn = ±1.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Vibration and rotation combined</div>
      <div class="btext">Real molecules vibrate AND rotate simultaneously. Total energy:</div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Combined energy</div>
        E = (n + ½)hf₀ + ℓ(ℓ+1)ℏ²/2I
      </div>
      <div class="btext">Transitions obey Δn = ±1 and Δℓ = ±1. This gives two branches in the IR spectrum:<br>
      <strong>R branch</strong>: Δℓ = +1 → lines at higher frequency than the vibrational frequency.<br>
      <strong>P branch</strong>: Δℓ = −1 → lines at lower frequency.<br>
      Each branch shows equally spaced lines with spacing 2ℏ²/I (the rotational spacing).</div>
      <div class="box box-m">Energy scale hierarchy (must memorize): Electronic ~ eV (UV/visible) &gt; Vibrational ~ 0.1 eV (IR) &gt; Rotational ~ meV (microwave). Exam problem: given a transition, identify which type it is from the photon wavelength.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- M2: Lasers -->
<div class="topic" id="m2">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">10.2</span><div><div class="t-name">Stimulated Emission & Lasers</div><div class="t-sub">Population inversion, three/four-level systems</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-key">§10.2</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Three processes of light-matter interaction</div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Absorption: atom in lower state E₁ absorbs photon → goes to E₂</div>
        E_photon = E₂ − E₁ = hf
      </div>
      <div class="btext"><strong>Spontaneous emission</strong>: atom in E₂ randomly decays to E₁, emits photon in random direction. Rate ∝ population of E₂.<br><br>
      <strong>Stimulated emission</strong>: incoming photon of frequency f triggers atom in E₂ to emit a second photon — identical frequency, phase, direction, polarization. This is coherent amplification. Rate ∝ (photon density) × (population of E₂).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Population inversion</div>
      <div class="btext">Normally (thermal equilibrium), lower energy states are more populated (MB: N₂/N₁ = e^(−ΔE/kT) &lt; 1). For laser action, you need <strong>population inversion</strong>: N₂ &gt; N₁ so stimulated emission dominates absorption. This cannot be achieved with a two-level system (absorption and stimulated emission are equally probable).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Three-level and four-level laser systems</div>
      <div class="btext"><strong>Three-level (e.g. Ruby)</strong>: pump to level 3, fast non-radiative decay to metastable level 2, laser transition 2→1 (ground state). Problem: must deplete ground state more than half — requires intense pumping.<br><br>
      <strong>Four-level (e.g. Nd:YAG, He-Ne)</strong>: pump to level 4, decay to metastable level 3, laser 3→2, fast decay back to ground 1. Level 2 is nearly always empty → inversion is easier to achieve. More efficient.</div>
      <div class="box box-m">LASER = Light Amplification by Stimulated Emission of Radiation. Three requirements: (1) gain medium, (2) population inversion via pumping, (3) optical cavity (mirrors) for feedback and coherence.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- M3: Structural Properties -->
<div class="topic" id="m3">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">10.3</span><div><div class="t-name">Structural Properties of Solids</div><div class="t-sub">Crystal types, X-ray diffraction, Bragg's law</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-std">§10.3</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Types of solids</div>
      <div class="box box-m">
        <strong>Ionic crystals</strong> (NaCl): held by Coulomb attraction between ions. Hard, high melting point, insulators.<br>
        <strong>Covalent solids</strong> (diamond, Si): shared electrons, strong directional bonds. Very hard.<br>
        <strong>Metallic</strong> (Cu, Fe): free electron gas, good conductors.<br>
        <strong>Molecular solids</strong> (ice, dry ice): van der Waals between molecules. Soft, low melting point.<br>
        <strong>Hydrogen-bonded</strong> (ice): directional H-bonds.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Crystal lattice structures</div>
      <div class="btext">Common cubic lattices: simple cubic (SC, 1 atom/cell), body-centered cubic (BCC, 2 atoms/cell), face-centered cubic (FCC, 4 atoms/cell). Lattice constant a = unit cell edge.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Bragg's law — X-ray diffraction</div>
      <div class="btext">X-rays of wavelength λ diffract off parallel crystal planes separated by distance d. Constructive interference when path difference = nλ:</div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Bragg's law — θ is glancing angle measured FROM the plane (not from normal)</div>
        2d · sin θ = nλ,   n = 1, 2, 3, ...
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Interplanar spacing for cubic lattice (Miller indices hkl)</div>
        d_hkl = a / √(h² + k² + l²)
      </div>
      <div class="box box-m">Exam workflow: given θ and λ → find d from Bragg. Given d and lattice type → find a. Or given a → find θ for each (hkl) plane. Remember (100): d = a, (110): d = a/√2, (111): d = a/√3.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- M4: Thermal & Magnetic -->
<div class="topic" id="m4">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">10.4</span><div><div class="t-name">Thermal & Magnetic Properties of Solids</div><div class="t-sub">Phonons, heat capacity, dia/para/ferromagnetism</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-key">§10.4</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Phonons</div>
      <div class="btext">Quantized lattice vibrations. Phonons are <strong>bosons</strong> (integer spin) with μ = 0 → follow Planck/Bose-Einstein distribution. Average phonon number per mode: ⟨n⟩ = 1/[e^(ℏω/kT) − 1].</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Einstein model of heat capacity</div>
      <div class="btext">All N atoms vibrate at the same frequency f₀. Each = independent quantum harmonic oscillator.</div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Einstein heat capacity</div>
        C_v = 3Nk(hf₀/kT)² · e^(hf₀/kT) / [e^(hf₀/kT) − 1]²
      </div>
      <div class="btext">Correct at high T. At low T: decays <em>exponentially</em> — this is wrong for real solids.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Debye model</div>
      <div class="btext">Allows range of phonon frequencies 0 to ω_D (Debye cutoff). Debye temperature θ_D = ℏω_D/k.</div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Low-T limit (T ≪ θ_D) — Debye T³ law</div>
        C_v ∝ T³
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">High-T limit (both Einstein and Debye) — Dulong-Petit</div>
        C_v → 3Nk = 3R per mole
      </div>
      <div class="box box-m">Physical reason for T³: at low T only long-wavelength (low-ω) phonons excited. Debye density of states g(ω) ∝ ω². Number of excited phonons ∝ T³ → total energy ∝ T⁴ → C_v = dE/dT ∝ T³.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Thermal expansion</div>
      <div class="btext">Due to asymmetry of the interatomic potential — it is not a perfect parabola. As T increases, atoms spend more time on the "softer" high-r side → average separation increases. If potential were perfectly symmetric (harmonic), no thermal expansion would occur.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Magnetic properties of solids</div>
      <div class="btext"><strong>Diamagnetism</strong>: all materials — induced magnetic moments oppose external field. Very weak, negative χ. Originates from orbital motion of electrons.<br><br>
      <strong>Paramagnetism</strong>: materials with unpaired electrons (permanent magnetic dipoles). Dipoles align with external field → positive χ. Random at high T (Curie law: M ∝ 1/T).<br><br>
      <strong>Ferromagnetism</strong> (Fe, Ni, Co): quantum exchange interaction causes neighboring dipoles to align parallel → macroscopic magnetization even without external field. Below Curie temperature T_C. Above T_C: becomes paramagnetic.<br><br>
      <strong>Antiferromagnetism</strong>: alternating antiparallel alignment → zero net magnetization. Below Néel temperature.</div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Curie law (paramagnetism)</div>
        M = C·B/T   (C = Curie constant)
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- M5: Superconductivity -->
<div class="topic" id="m5">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">10.5</span><div><div class="t-name">Superconductivity</div><div class="t-sub">Zero resistance, Meissner effect, Cooper pairs, BCS</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-new">§10.5–10.6</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">What is superconductivity?</div>
      <div class="btext">Below a critical temperature T_c, certain materials have exactly <strong>zero electrical resistance</strong>. Not just very small — actually zero. Current flows indefinitely without dissipation. First discovered by Kamerlingh Onnes in mercury (T_c = 4.2 K) in 1911.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Meissner effect</div>
      <div class="btext">A superconductor expels all magnetic flux from its interior — <strong>perfect diamagnetism</strong>. B = 0 inside. Surface currents flow to exactly cancel any applied field. This is NOT just perfect conductivity (a perfect conductor would trap flux) — the Meissner effect is a distinct thermodynamic property. Enables magnetic levitation.</div>
      <div class="btext">If the applied field exceeds a critical field H_c, superconductivity is destroyed.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">BCS theory & Cooper pairs</div>
      <div class="btext">Bardeen, Cooper, and Schrieffer (Nobel 1972) explained superconductivity. Mechanism: an electron moving through the lattice distorts it slightly (phonon), which attracts a second electron. These two electrons form a <strong>Cooper pair</strong> — a bound state via phonon exchange.<br><br>
      Cooper pairs have spin 0 (integer) → they are <strong>bosons</strong>. All Cooper pairs condense into the same ground state → macroscopic quantum coherence → no scattering → zero resistance.</div>
      <div class="eq eq-m">
        <div class="eq-lbl">BCS energy gap (binding energy of Cooper pair)</div>
        2Δ ≈ 3.52 kT_c
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Type I vs Type II superconductors</div>
      <div class="btext"><strong>Type I</strong>: single critical field H_c. Meissner effect complete below H_c. Most pure metals.<br><br>
      <strong>Type II</strong>: two critical fields H_c1 and H_c2. Between them: partial flux penetration in quantized vortices (mixed state). High-T superconductors (YBCO, cuprates) are Type II with T_c up to 135 K. Used in MRI, maglev.</div>
      <div class="box box-m">Applications: Josephson junctions (quantum interference devices, SQUIDs), maglev trains, MRI magnets, particle accelerator magnets, next-gen quantum computers.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

