<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════
     CHAPTER 11: SEMICONDUCTORS
═══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="sec-hdr" id="ch11">
  <div><div class="sec-num">Chapter 11</div><div class="sec-title" style="color:var(--p)">Semiconductor Theory & Devices</div></div>
  <span class="sec-tag st-p">§11.1 – 11.4</span>
</div>

<!-- P1: Band Theory -->
<div class="topic open" id="p1">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">11.1</span><div><div class="t-name">Band Theory of Solids</div><div class="t-sub">Origin of bands, band gaps, metals vs insulators vs semiconductors</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-hot">§11.1 · foundation</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">How bands form</div>
      <div class="btext">Isolated atom: discrete energy levels (1s, 2s, 2p, …). Two atoms: each level splits into bonding + antibonding (as in §10.1). N atoms: each level splits into N closely-spaced levels → a continuous <strong>band</strong>. Gaps between bands = forbidden energies where no Bloch states exist.</div>
      <div class="btext">Physical origin of gaps: electron waves (Bloch waves) diffract off the periodic lattice. At Brillouin zone boundaries (k = nπ/a), standing waves form — two standing waves with different charge distributions have different energies → gap.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Metals, insulators, semiconductors</div>
      <div class="box box-p">
        <strong>Metal</strong>: valence band partially filled OR bands overlap. Electrons at E_f can accept tiny energy → conductors.<br>
        <strong>Insulator</strong>: valence band completely full, conduction band empty, gap E_g &gt; 5 eV. kT at room temp can't excite electrons across.<br>
        <strong>Semiconductor</strong>: like insulator but small gap, E_g ~ 0.1–3 eV. Thermal excitation possible at room temperature.
      </div>
      <div class="btext">Key values: Si E_g = 1.1 eV (indirect gap). Ge E_g = 0.67 eV. GaAs E_g = 1.4 eV (direct gap). Diamond E_g = 5.5 eV (insulator).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Effective mass</div>
      <div class="btext">Electrons in a crystal accelerate according to the band curvature, not free-particle mass. Effective mass m* defined from the E-k dispersion:</div>
      <div class="eq eq-p">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Effective mass</div>
        1/m* = (1/ℏ²) · d²E/dk²
      </div>
      <div class="btext">At conduction band minimum: positive curvature → m*_e &gt; 0. At valence band maximum: negative curvature → m* &lt; 0 → <strong>holes</strong>.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Holes</div>
      <div class="btext">A missing electron near the top of the valence band behaves as a positive charge carrier with positive effective mass m*_h. Holes move in the same direction as E field (opposite to electrons). Holes have energy measured <em>downward</em> from the valence band maximum.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- P2: Semiconductor Theory -->
<div class="topic" id="p2">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">11.2</span><div><div class="t-name">Semiconductor Theory</div><div class="t-sub">Intrinsic, doping, carrier concentrations, Fermi level</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-hot">§11.2 · most tested</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Intrinsic semiconductors</div>
      <div class="btext">Pure semiconductor at T &gt; 0: thermal energy promotes electrons from valence to conduction band, creating equal numbers of electrons (n) and holes (p).</div>
      <div class="eq eq-p">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Intrinsic carrier concentration (n = p = nᵢ)</div>
        nᵢ = √(NcNv) · e^(−Eg/2kT)
      </div>
      <div class="btext">For Si at 300K: nᵢ ≈ 1.5 × 10¹⁰ cm⁻³. Fermi level sits approximately at midgap.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Extrinsic (doped) semiconductors</div>
      <div class="box box-p">
        <strong>n-type</strong>: add Group V (P, As, Sb) to Si. Extra electron donated to conduction band. Donor level just below E_c. Electrons = majority carriers.<br>
        <strong>p-type</strong>: add Group III (B, Al, Ga) to Si. Accepts electron from valence band, creating hole. Acceptor level just above E_v. Holes = majority carriers.
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-p">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Donor binding energy (hydrogen-like, screened)</div>
        E_d = (m*/m)(1/εᵣ²) · 13.6 eV
      </div>
      <div class="btext">For Si: E_d ≈ 0.025 eV ≈ kT at 300K → donors nearly fully ionized at room temperature.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Mass action law</div>
      <div class="eq eq-p">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Always true in thermal equilibrium</div>
        n · p = nᵢ²
      </div>
      <div class="btext">For n-type (n ≈ N_d): p = nᵢ²/N_d. If N_d = 10¹⁶ cm⁻³: p = 10²⁰/10¹⁶ = 10⁴ cm⁻³. Minority carriers suppressed enormously.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Fermi level shift upon doping</div>
      <div class="eq eq-p">
        <div class="eq-lbl">n-type: E_f moves toward conduction band</div>
        E_f = E_fi + kT · ln(N_d/nᵢ)
      </div>
      <div class="eq eq-p">
        <div class="eq-lbl">p-type: E_f moves toward valence band</div>
        E_f = E_fi − kT · ln(N_a/nᵢ)
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Conductivity</div>
      <div class="eq eq-p">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Total semiconductor conductivity</div>
        σ = e(nμ_e + pμ_h)
      </div>
      <div class="btext">For Si at 300K: μ_e ≈ 1350 cm²/V·s, μ_h ≈ 480 cm²/V·s. Conductivity increases with T (unlike metals) because nᵢ grows exponentially — this dominates over mobility decrease from phonon scattering.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- P3: Devices -->
<div class="topic" id="p3">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">11.3</span><div><div class="t-name">Semiconductor Devices</div><div class="t-sub">p-n junction, diode, LED, solar cell, transistor</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-hot">§11.3 · most tested</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">p-n junction at equilibrium</div>
      <div class="btext">Join p-type and n-type. Electrons diffuse to p-side, holes to n-side. Ionized donors (+) left on n-side, ionized acceptors (−) on p-side → <strong>depletion region</strong> with built-in electric field opposing diffusion. Equilibrium: Fermi levels align. No net current.</div>
      <div class="eq eq-p">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Built-in contact potential</div>
        V₀ = (kT/e) · ln(N_a N_d / nᵢ²)
      </div>
      <div class="btext">~0.6–0.7 V for Si. Thermal voltage kT/e = 0.026 V at 300K.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Ideal diode equation (Shockley)</div>
      <div class="eq eq-p">
        <div class="eq-lbl">p-n junction I-V characteristic</div>
        I = I₀ · [e^(eV/kT) − 1]
      </div>
      <div class="btext"><strong>Forward bias</strong> (V &gt; 0): exponential current rise. Barrier lowered → majority carriers flood across.<br>
      <strong>Reverse bias</strong> (V &lt; 0): I → −I₀. Barrier raised → only thermally generated minority carriers trickle across.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Light-emitting diode (LED)</div>
      <div class="btext">Forward biased p-n junction in a direct-gap semiconductor (GaAs, GaN). Electrons injected into p-side recombine with holes → emit photon with E = hf ≈ E_g. Photon wavelength: λ = hc/E_g. GaN gives blue/UV LEDs (Nakamura, Nobel 2014).</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Solar cell (photovoltaic)</div>
      <div class="btext">Reverse of LED. Photon with hf &gt; E_g absorbed → creates electron-hole pair. Built-in field of p-n junction separates them → current flows in external circuit. Open-circuit voltage ≈ V₀. Efficiency limited by: photons with hf &lt; E_g not absorbed; photons with hf ≫ E_g lose excess energy as heat.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Transistor (MOSFET)</div>
      <div class="btext">Metal-Oxide-Semiconductor Field-Effect Transistor. Gate voltage controls carrier density in the channel between source and drain. Positive gate voltage on n-channel MOSFET: attracts electrons → channel forms → current flows. Acts as voltage-controlled switch or amplifier. Basis of all modern digital logic.</div>
      <div class="box box-p">Moore's Law: transistor count on a chip doubles ~every 2 years. Now at ~10¹⁰ transistors per chip. Feature sizes approaching fundamental quantum limits — reason for interest in new materials (graphene, 2D materials) and quantum computing.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- P4: Nanotechnology -->
<div class="topic" id="p4">
  <div class="t-head" onclick="toggle(this.parentElement)">
    <div class="t-left"><span class="t-idx">11.4</span><div><div class="t-name">Nanotechnology</div><div class="t-sub">Quantum confinement, quantum dots, graphene</div></div></div>
    <div class="t-right"><span class="badge b-new">§11.4 · new content</span><span class="chev">▼</span></div>
  </div>
  <div class="t-body">
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Quantum confinement</div>
      <div class="btext">When a semiconductor structure is made small enough (comparable to the de Broglie wavelength of electrons, ~1–10 nm), the electrons are quantum mechanically confined. This discretizes the energy levels — instead of bands, you get quantized levels like a particle in a box. The energy spacing increases as size decreases.</div>
      <div class="eq eq-p">
        <div class="eq-lbl">Confinement energy (particle in 3D box) scales as</div>
        E_n ∝ 1/L²  (L = confinement dimension)
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Quantum dots</div>
      <div class="btext">Nanocrystals of semiconductor (~2–10 nm) confined in all 3 dimensions → fully discrete spectrum. <strong>Tunable bandgap</strong>: smaller dot → larger gap → shorter wavelength emission. Same material (CdSe) emits blue (small dot) to red (large dot) by simply changing size. Applications: QLED displays, biological imaging, solar cells.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="block">
      <div class="blabel">Graphene & 2D materials</div>
      <div class="btext">Graphene = single atomic layer of carbon in hexagonal lattice. Extraordinary properties: electrons behave as massless relativistic particles (Dirac fermions) → extremely high mobility. Mechanically strongest material known. Conducts heat extremely well. 2D confinement → new physics not present in bulk. Nobel 2010 (Geim, Novoselov).</div>
      <div class="box box-p">Nanotechnology is where semiconductor physics meets quantum mechanics directly. The particle-in-a-box and harmonic oscillator you solved in QM are the actual models for quantum dots and carbon nanotubes.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

